o, Sardinia, Italy":"Oristano, Sardegna, Italië"},"en":{"about 1064–7 February 1127":"about 1064–7 February 1127","1064–1127":"1064–1127","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1110–1182":"1110–1182","–Male":"Deceased","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1040–1090":"1040–1090","1080":"1080","about 1082":"about 1082","7 February 1127":"7 February 1127","1090":"1090","1 September 1090":"1 September 1090","1110":"1110","1064":"1064","1040":"1040","1182":"1182","1082":"1082","1127":"1127","1034":"1034","from 1082 to 1127":"from 1082 to 1127","about 1110":"about 1110","about 1064":"about 1064","Codrongianos, Sassari, Sardinia, Italy":"Codrongianos, Sassari, Sardinia, Italy","Arborea, Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardinia, Italy","Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy":"Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy","Torres, Sardegna, Italy":"Sardinia, Italy","Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Oristano, Sardinia, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Torres,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Carlos, Manuel, Jesus, Francisco, Pedro, Miguel, Jorge, Raul, Rafael.  Portuguese Ligia, Anatolio, Catarina, Paulo, Albeiro, Gonsalo, Joaquim, Lidio, Omero, Wenceslao.","Galician, Catalan, Spanish, Portuguese, and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from any of numerous places called Torres, all named with the plural of <i>torre</i> ‘tower’ (see   Torre  ). As a Jewish name, it was often adopted at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics. Compare   De Torres  .","Italian: habitational name from Torres in Belluno or Porto Torres in Sassari. In southern Italy the surname is sometimes of Spanish origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Torrez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Juan, Pedro, Carlos, Jesus, Armando, Raul, Ruben, Alfredo, Alvaro, Fernando.","Spanish (<b>Tórrez</b>): variant of   Torres  ."]},{"name":"Torre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Angelo, Salvatore, Carmelo, Vito, Antonio, Carmine, Pietro, Sal, Sebastiano, Agostino, Bartolo.  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Carlos, Julio, Alvaro, Eduardo, Elvira, Ernesto, Fernando, Gregorio, Guillermo, Jorge.","Italian: topographic name for someone who lived near a tower, <i>torre</i> (from Latin <i>turris</i>), usually a defensive fortification or watchtower, or a habitational name from any of the places called with this word, as for example Torre Annunziata or Torre del Greco in Naples province, Torre de’ Passeri (Pescara, Abruzzo), or Torre di Ruggiero (Catanzaro, Calabria). Compare   La Torre  .","Galician, Catalan, Aragonese, Spanish, and Portuguese: topographic name from <i>torre</i> ‘(watch) tower’ (of the same etymology as 1), or a habitational name from any of numerous places called (La) Torre in Spain and Portugal. Compare Spanish   De la Torre   and   La Torre  ."]}]},{"name":"Constantine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Constantinus</i>, a derivative of <i>Constans</i>;  see  Constant .  In early modern English the names <i>Constant</i> and <i>Constantine</i> were not always clearly distinguished. The Roman emperor  Constantine the Great  (  ?288–337 ) is specially honoured in the Christian Church as the first Christian emperor. The name was also borne by three kings of medieval Scotland, where it represents an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name   Conn  , and is a traditional name in the Phipps (Marquesses of Normanby) family."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Constantine I de Torres, Judge of Torres was born about 1064, in Oristano, Sardinia, Italy, his father, Mariano I di Lacon Gunale, Judge of Torres, was 32 and his mother, Susanna de Zori, was 25. He had at least 2 sons with Marcusa 'Maria' di Arrubu. He died on 7 February 1127, in Sardinia, Italy, at the age of 64, and was buried in Codrongianos, Sassari, Sardinia, Italy."},"et":{"about 1064–7 February 1127":"umbes 1064–7. veebruar 1127","1064–1127":"1064–1127","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1110–1182":"1110–1182","–Male":"Surnud","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1040–1090":"1040–1090","1080":"1080","about 1082":"umbes 1082","7 February 1127":"7. veebruar 1127","1090":"1090","1 September 1090":"1. september 1090","1110":"1110","1064":"1064","1040":"1040","1182":"1182","1082":"1082","1127":"1127","1034":"1034","from 1082 to 1127":"1082 kuni 1127","about 1110":"umbes 1110","about 1064":"umbes 1064","Codrongianos, Sassari, Sardinia, Italy":"Codrongianos, Sassari, Sardegna, Itaalia","Arborea, Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardegna, Itaalia","Logudoro, Sardinia, Italy":"Logudoro, Sardegna, Itaalia","Torres, Sardegna, Italy":"Sardegna, Itaalia","Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Oristano, Sardegna, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1064–7 February 1127":"noin 1064–7. helmikuuta 1127","1064–1127":"1064–1127","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1110–1182":"1110–1182","–Male":"Kuollut","1034–1082":"1034–1082","1040–1090":"1040–1090","1080":"1080","about 1082":"noin 1082","7 February 1127":"7. helmikuuta 1127","1090":"1090","1 September 1090":"1. s